against road crash victim</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is unfair and sends the wrong message. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Victims of culpable crash</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es deserve the same rights as other victims of crime. This is not happening despite the MOJ due to receive £30m from motoring offences each year.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Road crash victims need to be treated as victims of crime, until the contrary is proven. </span></li></ul><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local Justice workin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g groups to be established, similar to the Justice for Vulnerable Road Users Working Group established by the DfT.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">RoadPeace has supported crash victims and campaigned for safer roads and a fairer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> justice system since being founded in 1992 o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n the principle of road danger reduction.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Safety of cyclists has been a key issue for RoadPeace and our members from the start.  Christine Mangat was a founding member of RoadPeace after her son was killed cycling in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in 1989 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">when he was hit by a lorry at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Kings Cross in 198</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">9</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. She represented RoadPeace on the Independent Road </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Death Working Group (1992-94). After Janine Burke was killed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cycling by a cement mixer in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">February 1993, her mother Julie organised concerts and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sponsored the publication of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">our leaflet “Our Lost Children”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Also that year, Athene Hariades was killed whil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">st cycling in London </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and her death led to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> John Tavener composing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> “A Song for Athene”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and her mother volunteering on the RoadPeace helpline and organising our annual London rem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">embrance service</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Cynthia Barlow, our current Chair, became involved after her daughter Alex Jane was killed cycling to work in London in 2000 by a left turning lorry.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Now retired, she is a full time campaigner</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for victims rights and reducing the risk to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> road users, especially cyclists.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In association with the Cairns family, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">RoadPeace launched the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">See Me Save Me</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> campaign in 2011</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which called for lorry danger to be reduced with the blindspot eliminated. L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">orries kill more pedestrians than cyclists. Banni</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng the blind spot should mean visibility around the whole lorry, not just on the left hand side.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">RoadPeace responded to two cycle safety enquiries last year, that of the London Assembly in summer 2012 and the All Party Parliamentary Group on Cycling’s Ge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t Britain Cycling inquiry at the end of 2012. We also responded to the consultation on TfL’s draft Road Safety Plan and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have contributed to the development of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the individual </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pedestrian and cycle safety action plans</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">And credit should be given to TfL for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">adopting a systems approach with their new road safety plan and for their vision of streets free</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> from death and serious injury. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Their development of FORS and promotion at the national level shows a commitment to tackling danger at source. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">S CYCLING SAF</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">?</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Cycling is not as safe as it should be and could be.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is obviously not safe enough for the millions who </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">want to cycle but are too scared to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> It is not safe enough for cycling to deliver the huge public health benefits of which it is potentially capab</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">le.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It does not help to refer to “accidents” as this implies collisions cannot be avoided. Many MPs already appreciate the sensitivity around this issue and the need to use appropriate language. Just as it does not help to refer to cyclists being in colli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sions with cars or HGVs, when the reality is the cyclist has been run over and is the only victim in the vast majority of cycle collisions.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">YCLING SAFETY PRIORITIES</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In our earlier cycle safety consultation responses, w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e identified four key safety concerns to cyclists: </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">speed</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">junctions</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lorries</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lack of justice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-both in terms of traffic law enforcement and the post crash response</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our comments </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are drawn from our previous responses with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">priority given to highlighting actions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> outstanding and missed opportunities.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Speed</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Speed limits are too high and too rarely enforced. They should be reduced so that the risk of death to a cyclist in a crash is much closer to that of a car occupant. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Reducing vehicle speed was identified by T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">RL as the key way to improve cyclist safety.  Under current enforcement policy, drivers can do 42mph in a 30 mph speed limit before they are fined and given penalty points. This speed differential will be deadly to a cyclist or pedestrian. In comparison, S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">weden has moved to reduce their speed tolerance and have set a target of achieving 80% compliance with speed limits by 2020. On  unsegregated roads speed limits need to be reduced.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">And the priority need is not for speed reduction outside schools or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hospitals as this is not where the majority of collisions occur. Cyclist collisions are concentrated at junctions. All approaches to signalised junctions should have their speed limit reduced. This would also help to reduce red light running and other inju</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dicious/hasty/rash actions at junctions.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Research has also shown the effectiveness of intelligent speed adaptation (ISA) in increasing compliance with speed limits with one ISA equipped vehicle affecting the speed of 8-12 vehicles in London. RoadPeace has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> called for all government vehicles and those on government contracts to be required to use ISA.  TfL has promised a revolution in ISA but this is needed nationwide.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Junction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">s</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">TfL has prioritised improving the worst junctions for cyclists and much attenti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on is being given to them. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">But turning lorries are a problem at other junctions and low cost measures are needed. At the junction where Ellie Car</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y was killed, left turns have been banned. This was believed to be a first for London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> but should be considered</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> elsewhere</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Another</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> simple measure was suggested ten years ago by a bereaved father</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Turning traffic should be required to give way to traffic going forward, e.g. not changing direction. This is the law in the Netherlands where Brigitte Robinson grew up.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Brigitte was killed in London by a left turning lorry at a junction where she was going straight. Her father submitted a response to the Transport Committee in 2003, too much of which is still relevant.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Lorries</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whilst m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ost deaths, injuries and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">intimidation suffered by cyclists is from car drivers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he greatest risk of death to an urban cyclist is from a lorry. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A dual</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">approach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is needed if risk of death, injury and intimidation is to be reduced to cyclists.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As mentioned previously, our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">See Me Sa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ve Me</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> campaign was launched to tackle the outrageous situation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">where the heaviest and most unwieldy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> vehicles on our roads were allowed to travel with known blindspots.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> London has made effort in the past year to reduce lorry danger, including the research b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y Loughborough University. TfL has led the way with challenging the Health and Safety Executive and also the construction industry to do more to reduce road deaths.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Recent research on rigid lorries by Loughborough University has confirmed that mirrors, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">even the improved design, do not eliminate the blindspot. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Mayor has proposed a substantial daily charge for lorries operating without safety technology or sideguards,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">but why did it take so long and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">so many </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cyclist </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">deaths to suggest this?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Lack of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">justice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">--</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Traffic law enforcement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The risk of death and injury from the wrongdoings of another is greater on the roads than anywhere else. Yet the police do not prioritise the protection of life on the roads and roads policing remains the Cinderella of pol</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">icing.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Driving offences</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Relatively few drivers are prosecuted for dangerous driving or even careless driving. Drivers are much more likely to be convicted of drink driving than dangerous driving, but this is believed due to the ease at proving drink driv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing and the lack of traffic law enforcement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whilst surveys of drivers are conducted to estimate the incidence of mobile phone use, no such survey has been done of the extent of dangerous driving. Whilst it might only be a rough proxy, it would be bett</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">er than relying on dangerous or /careless driving offence statistics.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In our response to the DfT consultation on a Careless Driving Fixed Penalty Notice </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in summer 2012, RoadPeace argued that this FPN should be targeted in urban areas to remind </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">motorists of their duty of care towards vulnerable road users.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> In London, RoadPeace has proposed the MPS produce an annual traffic law enforcement plan and report on the delivery of the plan. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Enforcement of traffic regulations on cyclists would also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">discourage them from endangering themselves</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and ease some of the tensions between cyclists and motorists.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> It would also help the case for Presumed Liability compensation system, discussed later in this response.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Lack of justice--</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Post crash response</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Nation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wide, less than one out of three people injured in a crash bother reporting it to the police (DfT, 2013)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. It is feared to be even lower amongst injured cyclists.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For the 2012 parliamentary debate on cycling, RoadPeace produced a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> summary table on the jus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ce system, highlighting current problems and op</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">portunities for improvement with collision investigation, inquest, prosecution and sentencing, civil compensation and victims’ rights. These areas were also reviewed in our response to the APPG Cycling.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Colli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">sion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> investigation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Key </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">calls </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">included </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">greater transparency, accountability and priority with serious injury collision investigation, with the police: </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Reporting serious injury road crashes on the national Computer Recorded Information System (CRIS) s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o that their progress and outcome can be monitored. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Publishing their </span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">serious injury collision investigation procedures, and </span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">budget/resources allocated to serious injury investigation, and </span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">how they evaluate their collision investigation performance.</span></li></ul><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">App</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ointing a senior officer to lead on serious injury collision investigation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Including road crash maps in community consultations alongside crime maps.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Providing those seriously injured in road crashes with written information on the legal procedures that f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ollow, their rights and updates on the investigation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Extending Track my crime initiatives to include road crashes.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Producing an annual report on the legal outcome of fatal and serious injury investigations, as the Metropolitan Police Service are producing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Engaging the local community with regular updates on traffic law enforcement and collision investigation, as the Merseyside Police do at the bimonthly meetings of the RoadPeace North West Local Group which meets in the Merseyside Police Headquarters.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Criminal prosecution</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In their 2004 Traffic Law and its Enforcement report, the Transport Committee </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">highlighted </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the problem of in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">appropriate prosecution and sentencing. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he CPS updated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">their driving offences charging standards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Whilst the charging</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> standard for dangerous driving now includes more reference to failure to have due regard for vulnerable road users, no </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">changes were made to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">careless driving charging standards. Key calls</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">include</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Greater clarity around charging standards of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dangerous and careless driving, as there are very few examples given of what qualifies as careless driving and the border between these two charges is contentious.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Risk posed to vulnerable road users should justify a more serious charge.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">All prosecutors, i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ncluding police, need to receive specialised training in order to present the risks involved. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Monitoring of legal outcome, including downgrading, It should be possible to know how many drivers were prosecuted for killing/injuring a cyclist by driving dan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gerously or carelessly.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Dangerous driving prosecutions have decreased, including in fatal crashes. Concerns with the perceived failure of the justice system  has led the DfT to establish a Justice for Vulnerable Road Users working group. RoadPeace has cal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">led for a London Justice Working Group to be established, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd these should be established for every police area. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Victims Code</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">£30 million from motoring fines is to be transferred annually to the MOJ for victim services, but still, road crash victims do </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not have the same rights as other victims. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">MOJ’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> new Code of Practice fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r Victims of Crime </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">exclude</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> those injured by summary motoring offences</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Thus, those injured by drink drivers, careless drivers, speeding drivers, hit and run drivers, etc. do not qua</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lify for the rights under the new Code. The police do not have to keep them informed of the investigation pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gress or the charging decision. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">RoadPeace has argued that crash victims should be treated as victims of crime, until the contrary is proven. Britis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h Cycling, CtC, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and LCC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">support this call.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Without justice there can be no security for cyclists or other vulnerable road users, and this is essential for those wanting to cycle. Lack of confidence in our justice system is believed to pose a big barrier </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to cycling. A separate inquiry on traffic justice is needed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Civil justice and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Presumed/stricter liability</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Presumed or stricter liability involves reversing the burden of proof in collisions with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cyclists and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pedestrians for civil compensation claims. It </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">does not affect criminal liability. It is the civil compensation system that dominates in the rest of the world, including in Europe, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">especially </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">those countries where cycling is normalised/common. Countries with the most cycling protect cyclists and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> pedestrians through</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> presumed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">liability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> compensation systems</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, not helmets or hi viz clothing. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Civil liability reform is not new to the Transport Committee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and was proposed for further consideration in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">their 2004 Traffic law enforcement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">report. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Nor is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">this call new to RoadPeace as it was in our 1997 election manifesto. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our most recent briefing (June 2013) was</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> dedicated to Marie Vesco, a young French woman who was hit by one car exiting an A road and run over by a second car following too close to avoid </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hitting her. Her parents were shocked at the response by our justice system to their daughter’s death and are campaigning for presumed liability, as in France. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Nor are we alone in calling for liability reform. In 2013, both the Green Party and the Liberal Democrats supported stricter liability and it has recently been debated in the Scottish Parliament. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It should be noted that the reform proposed in Scotland devi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ates from the norm in that children, elderly and disabled can be held liable for co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ntributory negligence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This is not the practice in other countries where the super-vulnerable are treated as such. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">See our website for more information on who else supports </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and how it operates</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whilst the government has previously rejected calls for liability reform, this was reported due to the lack of evidence of it contributing to risk reduction. As with other programmes/measures introduced years ago and at the same ti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">me as other interventions, lack of evidence means just that—not evidence of no impact.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Its recent introduction in Luxembourg (December 2012) may provide evidence in time.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">RoadPeace has argued that it is needed for fairer and faster compensation, especially</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for children, elderly and disabled pedestrians and cyclists. Any subsequent reduction in risk would be an added bonus.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:0.96pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In conclusion, this inquiry is much appreciated as is the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Transport </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Committee’s ongoing commitment to making the roads safer and our justice system fairer for cyclists. RoadPeace looks forward to working with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Transport </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Committee on achieving this in 2014 and beyond, and repeats our call for an inquiry into traffic law </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">enforcement and justice. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>